'''Blair McDougall''' is a political activist in the British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], best known as head strategist to the [[Better Together (campaign)|Better Together]] campaign during the [[Scottish independence referendum, 2014|Scottish independence referendum]].

He was educated at the [[University of Glasgow]], where as chair of the Labour Club he was [[Ross Kemp]]'s campaign manager during the 1999 Rectorial election.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12007530.Grannie_competes_with_EastEnders_hardman_for_university_rector_apos_s_post/|title=Grannie competes with EastEnders hardman for university rector&apos;s post|date=2 February 1999|work=The Herald}}</ref> 

He went on to serve as chair of [[Scottish Labour Students]] 2001-2003 before becoming a [[Special advisers (UK government)|special adviser]] to [[Ian McCartney]], Minister for Trade, Foreign and Commonwealth Office and [[James Purnell]], Secretary of State for Culture, Media & Sport in the governments of [[Tony Blair]] and [[Gordon Brown]].

In 2006 he took the post of Youth Representative on the NEC (UK [[National Executive Committee]]).  

Following Labour's defeat in the 2010 [[General election (UK)|General election]], McDougall coordinated [[David Miliband]]'s unsuccessful campaign for the party leadership, and subsequently founded [http://www.movementforchange.org.uk/ Movement for Change], an umbrella group for [[Community organizing|community organisers]]. He became Campaign Director of Better Together in 2012.

After the No vote in the referendum on 18 September 2014, McDougall was given an advisory role in [[Jim Murphy|Jim Murphy's]] campaign for the Scottish Labour leadership. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/blair-mcdougall-lands-jim-murphy-advisor-role-1-3590464|title=Blair McDougall lands Jim Murphy advisor role|website=www.scotsman.com|access-date=2016-07-22}}</ref>

McDougall was confirmed as the Scottish Labour candidate for [[East Renfrewshire (UK Parliament constituency)|East Renfrewshire]] in the 2017 UK general election. He came third in that election, with 26.7% of the vote, a fall in the Labour vote of over 7 points as compared with the 2015 election, in which Labour candidate [[Jim Murphy]] came second with 34% of the vote.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2018-03-13|title=East Renfrewshire (UK Parliament constituency)|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=East_Renfrewshire_(UK_Parliament_constituency)&oldid=830201578|journal=Wikipedia|language=en}}</ref>

