The term '''dominant portion''' is used in [[measurement]] of room spaces for [[Real estate appraisal|valuation or appraisal]] purposes.

The dominant portion is defined as:
*the largest solid or [[glass]] area making up the inside finished surface, along a single [[plane (geometry)|plane]], of the total permanent outer building [[wall]].<ref>[http://www.tbs-sct.gc.ca/rpm-gbi/lexicon-lexique/term-terme.asp?Language=EN&id=763 Dominant Portion<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031126185025/http://www.tbs-sct.gc.ca/rpm-gbi/lexicon-lexique/term-terme.asp?Language=EN&id=763 |date=November 26, 2003 }}</ref>
*the portion of the inside finished surface of the permanent outer building wall which is 50% or more of the vertical [[floor]] to [[ceiling]] dimension measured at the dominant portions. If there is no dominant portion, or if the dominant portion is not [[vertical direction|vertical]], the measurement for area shall be to the inside finished surface of the permanent outer building wall where it intersects the finished floor.<ref>[http://www.bethesda-office-space.com/Bethesdaofficespacemeasurement.html Bethesda Office Space Measurement Rules<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208075250/http://www.bethesda-office-space.com/Bethesdaofficespacemeasurement.html |date=February 8, 2012 }}</ref>

The second definition particularly applies to measurement of [[office space]]s based on the [[Building Owners and Managers Association]] measurement.

