{{refimprove|date=August 2016}} {{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}} {{Infobox park | name = St. Thomas' Peace Garden | photo = St Thomas' Peace Garden, Birmingham, UK.jpg | photo_width = | photo_caption = The remains of [[St. Thomas' Church, Birmingham|St. Thomas' Church]] | map = | map_width = | type = | location = [[Birmingham]], [[England]] | nearest_city = | coords = {{coord|52.4734|N|1.906|W|region:GB-BIR|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | coords_ref = | area = | created = {{Start date|df=yes|1995}} | operator = [[Birmingham City Council]] | visitation_num = | status = | awards = | open = | website = <!-- {{URL|http://www.birmingham.gov.uk/XXXX}} --> }}
'''St Thomas' Peace Garden''' (aka the '''Peace Gardens''') is a small [[public park]] in [[Birmingham]], England,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.parksandgardens.org/places-and-people/site/8372/summary | title=Peace Gardens, Birmingham, (also known as St. Thomas' Peace Garden), England | website=Parks and Gardens UK | accessdate=26 August 2016 }}</ref> designated as a monument to [[peace]] and a memorial to all those killed in armed conflict.
The Peace Gardens were designed around the tower and west porticos of [[St. Thomas' Church, Birmingham|St Thomas's Church]], Bath Row, which was half demolished in the [[Birmingham Blitz]] in 1940 and never restored.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}} The grounds were laid out in 1955 to commemorate the coronation of [[Queen Elizabeth II]]. They were redesigned in 1995 to commemorate the fiftieth anniversary of the end of World War II. When the world leaders came to Birmingham for the [[24th G8 summit|G8 summit]] in 1998, each planted a tree. Each premier chose a tree that most represented their respective countries and they are now a living symbol of peace. Although the Peace Garden is within St Thomas' grounds this is a site that is for everyone including the ever-growing numbers of non-religious people of Birmingham, the [[West Midlands (region)|West Midlands]] and the world.
==St. Thomas' Church== [[File:St. thomas church brum.jpg|thumb|left|upright|St Thomas' Church in the 1880s]] Following victory in the [[Battle of Waterloo]] in 1815, Parliament set up a Commission that was given £1million to build so called '[[Commissioners' Church|Waterloo Churches]]' in an act of national thanksgiving in 1818.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}} Two of the Commissioners' churches in Birmingham were designed in a [[Neoclassical architecture|neo-classical]] style by [[Thomas Rickman]], St. Thomas' and St. Peter's, Dale End in 1825 (now demolished).
St Thomas' was described at the time as 'of great simplicity, and in every respect consistent with the sacred purpose to which it is dedicated.'{{citation needed|date=August 2016}} The neo-classical rather than gothic designs may have been the result of a rumour in The Quarterly Review, later denied, that the Commissioners wanted no more gothic churches.
The reason may have been economic, however; Commission Minute Books indicate that Rickman produced two early English designs which would have been more expensive than the neo-classical designs which were finally accepted.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}} The foundation stone of the church was laid by the Bishop of Worcester on 22 October 1826 and three years afterwards the building was completed, being consecrated on 22 October 1829.
==Birmingham Blitz== {{main article|Birmingham Blitz}} On the night of 11 December 1940, all but the fine tower of St Thomas' and classical west portico was destroyed by German bombs.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}} The church was never rebuilt. The grounds were laid out for the coronation of Queen Elizabeth II in 1953 when the gravestones were removed and the dead reinterred at [[Warstone Lane Cemetery]].
==Peace gardens== [[File:Tower of St Thomas in the Peace Garden, Birmingham west end.JPG|thumb|upright|The remaining tower as part of the Peace Garden]] The gardens were re-designed as the Peace Garden in 1995 in commemoration of the fiftieth anniversary of the end of [[World War II]].{{citation needed|date=August 2016}} The First World War Memorial [[colonnade]], which had been built as part of the [[Hall of Memory (Birmingham)|Hall of Memory]] to designs by [[S. N. Cooke]] and W. N. Twist, in 1925, was relocated here when [[Centenary Square]] was laid out 1989. Railings with doves of peace were erected, sculpted by [[Anuradha Patel (sculptor)|Anuradha Patel]].
Within the Peace Garden is a memorial to British service personnel who were killed or injured as a result of nuclear weapons testing in the [[Pacific Ocean]].{{citation needed|date=August 2016}}
When the world leaders came to Birmingham for the G8 summit in 1998, each planted a tree here.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}} Each premier choose a tree that most represented their respective countries and they are now a living symbol of peace.
The spire of St Thomas’ Church is in need of extensive repair work{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}, its stonework is deteriorating rapidly and the golden ball and cross from the top was lost some years ago. St. Thomas' Peace Garden forms the centre of a square bound by part of Washington and Granville Streets, Bath Row and Ridley Street. Following the major development of [[Lee Bank]] in the 1960s, the square was surrounded by many poor quality buildings including a large bingo hall, however a regeneration plan for the area has begun{{when|date=February 2015}} and there are a number of new apartments and offices surrounding the square.
